Ferrari's Monegasque driver Charles Leclerc drives during the second practice session ahead of the 2022 Saudi Arabia Formula One Grand Prix. AFP/Andrej Isakovic JEDDAH - Sunday's Saudi Arabian Grand Prix will go ahead despite a missile attack on an oil facility in Jeddah. Friday's attack close to the track disrupted practice ahead of Saturday's qualifying session. READ: Saudi Arabian Formula 1 practice delayed after rebel attack on oil facility Drivers met for four hours last night, discussing whether the race should proceed. The decision to race was made in the early hours of Saturday morning after reassurances from team bosses. Ferrari again looks like the team to beat this weekend after their victory in the season-opening race in nearby Bahrain.